\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 My own gardening efforts have been haphazard. The lack of access to my college email\'92s Google Drive, cut off in mid-September, prompted another storage crisis for me, and I tried to download all of the material in my email and drive to my computer. This proved a surprisingly hard and lengthy process, and despite the promises of Google TakeOut, I ended up with a half-downloaded drive and some email settings in a zip file. I then tried to doctor the half-downloaded material, adding and rearranging it. 
\f4\i Then 
\f0\i0 I realized that I could share the drive, and simply copy over the material of the original into my current Google Drive. I went through each folder and copied all of the material into a corresponding folder, organizing as I went. This means I now have a second bastardized version of my Google drive, and am well on my way to ship-of-Theseus-ing every Google Doc I\'92ve worked on. \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 My mother also regularly prunes her photos, often immediately deleting all but the best take of a picture, which means she keeps an enviably meaningful and sparse collection. Elimination of detritus and bloated files can be a protective act of care for your own data, both decreasing what you send to those long hot-and-cold server hallways and making it easier for what you want to live on to actually live on. But even when I went through all of my photos in making those photo albums three years ago, I couldn\'92t bear to delete those photos of my receipts or all of the alternative angles of a selfie. What I didn\'92t print out at the CVS kiosk now lives in organized folders on a hard drive. \
\
Why can\'92t I delete? Why am I so attached to my own Self represented in this way? Well, I\'92ve been reading Simone Weil (Gravity and Grace (
\f4\i link)
\f0\i0 , specifically) and can now diagnose myself with an inability to accept death. \'93May God grant me to become nothing,\'94 she wrote. For Weil, the self is \'93only the shadow which sin and error cast by stopping the light of God, and I take this shadow for a meaning.\'94 The self blocks God from the world, like an \'93unwelcome third who is with two betrothed lovers and ought to go away so that they can really be together.\'94 We must renounce the self by dying a mini-death in order to \'93liberate a tied-up energy.\'94 I suspect that Weil would not have a storage problem in her photos app if she lived now. Could deleting photos, including meaningful ones, be that mini-death? Could it be an act of \'93accept[ing] the past without asking for future compensation\'94? Of \'93stop[ping] time at the present instant\'94? Of \'93accept[ing] death,\'94 of \'93reduc[ing] ourselves to the point we occupy in space and time \'97 that is to say, nothing\'94? \
