\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 If you live in the world right now, you\'92ve likely accumulated a vast library of personal data: photos, videos, voice memos, emails, app settings, files. Maybe you\'92re begrudgingly paying a monthly fee to maintain this data in the shadow-world of cloud storage. Maybe you\'92ve lost entire years of photos when you dropped your phone into the toilet of a Greyhound bus headed to New York when you were eighteen. You might be very aware of the photos \'93a year ago today\'94 and you might confront faces\'a0 that you\'92ll never see again in person at the altar of your Photos app.\'a0
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 Every day, we build on our own collection of data. What responsibilities do we have to our own archives? In this (inaugural) blog post, I\'92m going to explore a couple of art pieces that I\'92ve experienced over the past couple of months to try to answer this question.\'a0
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 In the summer\'92s-winter of late June in Canberra, Australia, a strange government town plastered with posters protesting kangaroo road deaths, the artist and researcher Yann Seznec presented \'93The Memory Cloud.\'94 In this project, he extracted the audio out of every video in his personal cloud library and used this collection as a basis for a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.yannseznec.com/docs/projects/memory-cloud/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 granular synthesizer}}. With this synthesizer he can shuffle through the soundtrack of his memories at random, messing with the pitch and other parameters.
\f1\fs24 \
\

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 Yann emphasizes the philosophical implications of this instrument: firstly, the \'93overly saturated\'94 paradigm of photo and video storage that we have right now, where massive tech companies allow us to access any of our photos at all times. But these storage systems are incredibly platform-specific, profiting off of the dependence of their users. While converting all of his videos into just audio, and then repeating the process with another artist, Yann experienced deep friction at every step: we are not meant to own and manipulate our files in this way.\'a0
